IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: Tri-State Bird Rescue & Research, Inc. is a licensed wildlife rehabilitation organization and that provides expert rehabilitative care to injured, orphaned, or oiled native wild birds and wildlife, responds to oil spills, and leads wildlife readiness-response drills and contingency planning activities. Our mission is to achieve excellence in the rehabilitation of injured, orphaned, and oiled native wild birds, with the goal of returning healthy birds to their natural environment. This is accomplished through expert rehabilitative compassionate care, humane research, and education.
IRS990.MissionDesc: The mission of Tri-State Bird Rescue & Research is to achieve excellence in the rehabilitiation of injured, orphaned and oiled native wild birds, with the goal of returning healthy birds to their environment. We do this through compassionate care, humane research and education. Tri-State Bird Rescue & Research, Inc. is a licensed wildlife rehabilitation organization that provides expert rehabilitative care to injured, orphaned, or oiled native wild birds and wildlife, responds to oil spills, and leads wildlife readiness-response drills and contingency planning activities.
IRS990.Desc: FY2018 Bird Preservation & Protection Programs: BIRD CAREThe clinic admitted 3,302 birds between these dates. Over 119 different neotropical species which included over 1,800 individuals. Some of the specialty birds that the clinic admitted were: 64 bald eagles, 4 American kestrels, 16 common loons, 5 peregrine falcons, 51 Great-horned owls, and 49 Great blue herons. The number one species represented in the clinic was the American robin making up 25.3% of our caseload (835 individuals). The 3 most represented taxonomic groups admitted to the center were songbirds at 67.2% (2,219 individuals), raptors at 14.8% (488 individuals) and waterfowl at 8.7% (287 individuals). The clinic released over 977 individuals during the above time period with a survival rate after the first 24 hours of 68.91%. Out of those released over 100 orphans were reunited with their parents or placed in a foster family (non-biological). 40 of which were raptors including peregrine, bald eagles, ospreys and American kestrels. The clinic also reunited or fosterd 20 waterfowl and 41 songbirds. Some of the causes of injury that the clinic sees is: attack by cat (212 individuals), over 183 individuals attacked by another animal, hit by vehicle (325 individuals), 38 individuals gunshot victims, contamination (40 individuals) and West Nile Virus (19 individuals). The summer is the busiest time of year. During the summer the clinic admitted 2,450 hatch year birds and at its height admitted 44 birds in one day. The three most common cities that we receive admissions from are Wilmington at 29.3% (967 individuals), Newark at 27.8% (918 individuals) and New Castle at 8.1% (267 individuals).

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: FY2018 Bird Preservation & Protection Programs: OIL SPILL RESPONSE & CONTINGENCY PLANTri-State Bird Rescue and Research Oil Spill Programs staff is dedicated to oil spill planning and preparedness. The Oil Team, along with Core Team members and interns, have presented at and attended meetings and conferences such as the Delmarva Ornithological Society Meeting, Sector Delaware Bay Area Committee Meeting, RRT II, RRT V, Exxon Gibbstown and Paulsboro Community Advisory Panel (GAPCAP) Meeting, International Effects of Oil on Wildlife Conference, Emergency Preparedness and Hazmat Response Conference, National Wildlife Rehabilitators Association Symposium, and No Spills Conference. The team also secured contracts to write Wildlife Contingency Plans, pre-identify resources and teach workshops. The Oil Spill Response Team maintains availability 24/7 and has been able to respond to incidents. The Tri-State team was not only called out for responses, but also for assessments to survey spill sites for potentially oiled wildlife. Oiled wildlife responses involved capture, stabilization, wash, and release of affected waterfowl, raptors, shorebirds and reptiles. Tri-State Oil Programs staff also held workshops on oiled wildlife response for agency and industry partners, rehabilitators and volunteers.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: FY2018 VOLUNTEER SERVICES AND EDUCATION SERVICESThis program includes training volunteers and educational workshops for the public. The Tri-State team invests a lot of training into their volunteers to prepare them for their specific jobs. Tri-State Bird Rescue also does a lot of educational workshops for the public, as well as their volunteer training.

ProgSrvcAccomActyOtherGrp.Desc: FY2018 Bird Preservation & Protection Programs: EDUCATIONEducation is an important component of TSBRR's mission. It is achieved by providing information for the public as well as through colleague outreach, and intern and volunteer programs. TSBRR supported improved excellence in wildlife care by training other wildlife professionals, oil spill contingency personnel, and over 203 students and volunteers. TSBRR staff and volunteers presented topics at local, regional and international conferences. Through cooperative work with universities, TSBRR provided clinical opportunities for 23 veterinary students, 1 vet tech student and 21 life science students. TSBRR provided community service opportunities for several youth organizations, and participated in human collaborative research with 8 organizations, agencies and/or universities. Throughout the year, TSBRR helped to educate the public by answering thousands of telephone inquiries and conducting outreach programs. In addition, an annual open house is held each spring attracting hundreds of visitors to the campus in Newark, DE.

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The TSBRR Endowment is intended to perpetuate the mission of achieving excellence in the rehabilitation of injured, orphaned and oiled native wild birds. Endowment funds are invested and a portion of investment returns are used to fund general operations.

In accordance with FASB ASC 740-10, management continually evaluates uncertain tax positions and expiring statutes of limitations, audits, proposed settlements, changes in tax law and new authoritative rulings as applicable. Management's evaluation is that there is no additional income tax liability. This evaluation is based on settled and established rulings within the Internal Revenue code. Management believes there is no significant uncertainty related in its evaluation. The Organization's policy is to expense all interest and penalties, if any, as incurred.
